"The Linux/Unix host has one or more packages installed that are impacted by a vulnerability without a vendor supplied
patch available.

  - fastd is a VPN daemon which tunnels IP packets and Ethernet frames over UDP. When receiving a data packet
    from an unknown IP address/port combination, fastd will assume that one of its connected peers has moved
    to a new address and initiate a reconnect by sending a handshake packet. This fast reconnect avoids
    having to wait for a session timeout (up to ~90s) until a new connection is established. Even a 1-byte UDP
    packet just containing the fastd packet type header can trigger a much larger handshake packet (~150 bytes
    of UDP payload). Including IPv4 and UDP headers, the resulting amplification factor is roughly 12-13. By
    sending data packets with a spoofed source address to fastd instances reachable on the internet, this
    amplification of UDP traffic might be used to facilitate a Distributed Denial of Service attack. This
    vulnerability is fixed in v23. (CVE-2025-24356)

Note that Nessus relies on the presence of the package as reported by the vendor.");
